<paragraph id="0EC17C78F3ECB65772D4EA481B32C2B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="34172D5C865D2F6E49FB3DD96CC7EA8E" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName id="F3590A0F86EB63947D6967E5D85728DA" baseAuthorityName="Malling &amp; Gronwall" baseAuthorityYear="1909" genus="Archaeotolithus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archaeotolithus bornholmiensis" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="bornholmiensis">
<emphasis id="098319473E722DA81C898164857CB103" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Archaeotolithus bornholmiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species in the genus with almost no indication of a sulcus and further differs from its congeners in the more strongly convex inner face. It is thus also the one most resembling the characteristics of a lapillus.
</paragraph>
